               <NUMEX TYPE="ORDINAL">First</NUMEX> off, to all you
speed <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">demons</ENAMEX> who claim <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Java</ENAMEX> will soon be as fast as <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT">C/C++</ENAMEX> and who rightly point
to some of the work on making <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Java</ENAMEX> much faster: You are <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">half</NUMEX>-right. There is a
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">great</ENAMEX> deal of effort afoot to make <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Java</ENAMEX> faster (just-in-time compilation,
<ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">native</ENAMEX>-code generation, etc.). However <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Java</ENAMEX> will never be as fast as
<ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT">straight C/C++</ENAMEX>; there are too many <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">rich</ENAMEX> features of the language (garbage
collection, array-and-string bounds checking, dynamically loaded classes) for
it to ever be as fast as raw <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT">C/C++</ENAMEX>. Yes, I agree that the differences will
